The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 31, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 30: The government will file next week the draft prospectus for sale of its equity in NTPC, power minister P. M. Sayeed said today. I have signed the papers. The draft prospectus will be filed with the Sebi on Tuesday, he said. NTPC would file a combined prospectus for selling 5.25 per cent government stake and initial public offering for an equal quantity. The state-run power major is likely to hit the market around mid-September, Sayeed added.																								 New Delhi, July 30: The Murugappa group, with a turnover of Rs 5,520 crore, has decided to merge its companies  TI Diamonds Chains India Ltd with Tube Investments of India Ltd (TII). The share-swap ratio has been fixed at 4:5  four shares of TII for five of TIDC.																								 Mumbai, July 30: Bharat Petroleum Corp has offered to take Hindustan Petroleum as equal partner in the Rs 6,354-crore Bina refinery in Madhya Pradesh, said S. Behuria, BPCL chairman.																								 Mumbai, July 30: The rupee staged a rally against the dollar today. It closed at 46.43/45, up from Thursdays close of 46.46/47 to a dollar.																								 Mumbai, July 30: The Investors Grievances Forum has sought complete disclosures on the governments decision to place Global Trust Bank under moratorium and its proposed merger with the Oriental Bank of Commerce.
